No safety-relevant drift found inside src/mutex.rs itself.

The module is sequentially tight: M1-M10 invariants are maintained by init/try_lock/
lock_blocking/unlock; lock_decide/unlock_decide enumerate all input cases and their
postconditions match the code; overflow (M10) is enforced by the try_lock precondition
lock_count < u32::MAX and by the Overflow arm in lock_decide; underflow is impossible
because unlock's lock_count>1 branch is guarded and the lock_count==1 path assigns 0
directly. The priority-inheritance / owner_orig_prio path of Zephyr mutex.c is
explicitly declared out-of-scope and pushed to the C shim (ffi/src/lib.rs comments
at lines 468-469, 616, 682), so its absence from src/mutex.rs is a scoping decision
rather than a drift inside this file. A full ASIL-D assessment of priority-inversion
prevention must be filed against the FFI/C boundary, not src/mutex.rs.
